A Network Ad Wrangler Undaunted by Facebook and Google



Advertising 
By                     
 SAPNA MAHESHWARI
 
MAY 14, 2017




Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story










Photo






Linda Yaccarino, the head of advertising sales for NBCUniversal, at the company’s headquarters in New York on Thursday. The central question for ad sales? “It’s about the media mix,” she said.

Credit
            Tawni Bannister for The New York Times        



After completing her first year as the head of advertising sales for NBCUniversal, Linda Yaccarino went out to dinner with her husband to celebrate.She soon found herself crying into a bowl of shrimp scampi.The problem wasn’t the food. “My last name is Yaccarino — I friggin’ love shrimp scampi,” she said at an industry event last year.The tears were a rare reaction to what she called the hardest year of her career, when Ms. Yaccarino started dragging an ad sales operation for television programming as varied as “Sunday Night Football,” “Saturday Night Live” and Bravo reality shows into the digital future.Things haven’t gotten any easier in the television ad world, but five years later, Ms. Yaccarino, 54, is still at it. And far from weeping, she has become an outspoken leader in an industry that is contending with far-reaching changes in how people watch television while competing against a host of technology companies that have begun to vie for those same audiences by investing in original video content. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Ms. Yaccarino, who oversees $10 billion in annual ad revenue, has drawn particular attention for her vocal criticism of Nielsen ratings, which have long been the standard for how TV ads are bought and sold, and for her use of digital properties that NBCU has either invested in or forged partnerships with, like Snapchat, BuzzFeed and Apple News.“Linda has the ability to stay a step ahead, and I think she’s done that wherever she’s been,” said Julie Rieger, the executive vice president for media at 20th Century Fox, who has known Ms. Yaccarino for more than a decade. “She is in some ways the Wayne Gretzky of media. It’s not about where the puck is — it’s about where the puck is going.”As broadcast television audiences shrink and people spend more time on digital platforms, Ms. Yaccarino has reoriented herself to think of the competitive landscape as stretching beyond NBC’s rival networks to include online behemoths like Facebook and Google. During this week’s annual ritual known as upfronts, when networks trot out their biggest stars and announce new shows in an attempt to lure advertising dollars, Ms. Yaccarino will surely be promoting the fact that the NBCU universe includes more than 17 cable channels, 50 online destinations and partnerships that reach to all sorts of platforms and devices.
Photo






Ms. Yaccarino outside NBCUniversal’s headquarters on Thursday.

Credit
            Tawni Bannister for The New York Times        


During a recent interview in her sun-filled office, Ms. Yaccarino explained the ways that marketers might use NBCU’s properties and partnerships to reach, say, a young, busy mother.First, she wakes up and checks Apple News on her phone, Ms. Yaccarino said. Then she might turn on the “Today” show while making breakfast, catch up on E! on Snapchat at the school drop-off and check stock prices on CNBC or sports scores during the day. In the evening, she’ll tune in to a show like “This Is Us,” then end the evening watching Jimmy Fallon. Each presents a distinct marketing opportunity.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

“It’s about the media mix,” she said.Ms. Yaccarino’s desk faces two flat-screen televisions mounted side by side, and her office is peppered with photographs of stars like the Kardashians, whom she adores in part because of E!’s success in marketing their reality show. She’s married with two children, but jokes that Jack Pearson, the character from “This Is Us,” will be her second husband once she figures out what to do with the first. And she professes excitement for the “pinch me” moments in her job, like holding business meetings with Mr. Fallon and talking with Megyn Kelly about her move from Fox to NBC.She has forged new relationships, inviting the sales chief of a rival network to speak at an NBCU innovation event this year and teaming up with AOL for automated advertising a couple of years ago — when the notion was viewed as “heresy in the TV world,” Ms. Yaccarino said.Ms. Yaccarino joined NBCU in 2011, shortly after Comcast took control. She had spent more than 15 years at Turner Entertainment, where she earned a reputation for selling creatively designed ad space, like commercials tied to specific TV scenes, and for being, as Ms. Rieger said, both tough and “charming as hell.” (Her negotiating skills earned her the nickname “the Velvet Hammer,” a media buyer once told The Wall Street Journal.)She first oversaw sales for NBCU’s cable channels and was quickly promoted to overseeing all of the network’s ad sales, a move that combined its broadcast, cable and digital properties for the first time.Previously, sales teams for divisions like NBC Sports, Bravo and USA functioned independently of one another. With the new structure, the idea was that if buyers wanted to be on “The Voice” or “Sunday Night Football,” they could also be sold on “Modern Family” reruns, Bravo shows and more, providing the network with more scale and efficiency.Wrangling a 1,000-plus person organization and 15 teams into doing that was the grueling part for Ms. Yaccarino. But it also forced her to grow comfortable with acting quickly in an industry where her competitors were changing by the day.“Her job is understanding the marketplace and how to combine the assets she has under NBCU, connecting the dots between all the channels and ensuring the parent company gets as much revenue as possible,” said Irwin Gotlieb, the chairman of GroupM, the media investing arm of the ad giant WPP. While that may occasionally make it harder for buyers, he said, “that’s what she does, and she does it well.”If that was Act 1 of Ms. Yaccarino’s time at NBCU, she’s now ready for Act 2.“The next frontier is: How do we really bring it all together in terms of linear and digital?” she said.


            TV and Digital Fall Preview        

            Networks navigate an arena where advertisers and audiences waver between digital streaming platforms and broadcast television.        




 



“Imagine if the advertising-supported ecosystem went away,” she said. “There would be no Hulu, no Netflix, no Amazon, because that’s what fuels all their content. They’d have to go to 100 percent original, and the cost for the consumer would be absolutely unaffordable. So I think everyone agrees that advertising-supported content needs to remain the main driver or the epicenter of the business. We just need to figure out a way to do it respectfully to consumer behavior today.”

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Ms. Yaccarino has found her ambitions at odds with Nielsen, which has faced criticism from executives over what they have called outdated measurement tactics. CNBC stopped relying on Nielsen ratings in 2015, saying they weren’t properly accounting for viewing outside the home. In the fall, Ms. Yaccarino said Nielsen’s new product for counting viewers across traditional TV and devices like Roku and smartphones was too flawed for release. Nielsen declined to comment for this article.In March, she announced that  NBCU would offer up to $1 billion in non-Nielsen ad inventory that relies on its own audience data, including set-top box information from Comcast.
