The frustrations have cast old rivalries in a new light. Joe Marchese, who was named the head of ad sales at Fox Networks Group last week, was invited by Ms. Yaccarino to speak at an internal NBCU event this year.“It was kind of like a Macy’s-Gimbels type of thing for her to invite a senior person from Fox to come up and talk about where the industry is headed,” Mr. Marchese said. But it reflects the challenges networks are facing as some viewers opt out of ads entirely through platforms like Netflix, while at the same time TV ratings numbers are being compared with online ad views on Google and Facebook.TV executives have seethed in the past two years over a frequently repeated remark from Sheryl Sandberg, Facebook’s chief operating officer, who said the social network has a Super Bowl on mobile every day in terms of the people it can reach. While the size of audiences on Facebook and YouTube are undeniable, there is fierce debate over the value of video views on such platforms, particularly when the ads take up only, say, half of the screen, or appear for a couple of seconds without sound.“From a consumer experience, we all know what it’s like to experience a Super Bowl as you have people over your home, family, friends, or you go somewhere and you’re watching this communal experience and you’re talking about the show and you’re yelling and screaming and holding your breath and talking about the commercials,” Ms. Yaccarino said. “That’s a Super Bowl.”She held up her phone and exaggeratedly swiped the screen without breaking eye contact. “Does this look like a Super Bowl?” She kept swiping. “This is not a Super Bowl.”NBC, it should be noted, will air the game next year.While much has been said about technology companies coming for TV advertising dollars, Ms. Yaccarino said the companies were “really coming for TV content.” She pointed to Twitter’s and Amazon’s deals with the N.F.L. and YouTube’s new ad-supported shows with stars like Ryan Seacrest and Ellen DeGeneres.“Really, you just can’t snap your fingers and invent that,” she said of premium content.And that is why she believes her focus on aligning with tech companies and reaching a large number of people on a variety of platforms will pay dividends.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

“It’s about real audiences, real people who buy stuff, because they experienced your content all throughout the day,” she continued. “If we can do that, then we can really compete with the Google, Facebooks, Twitter, etc., etc., or whoever’s next of the world.”
Continue reading the main story






